But if you post, it's going
to move very, very slowly.

01:01:53.110 --> 01:01:55.370
You can drive policy a
little bit further ahead,

01:01:55.370 --> 01:01:58.240
but you saw the
process of Mercury.

01:01:58.240 --> 01:02:00.540
And that's the easy one.

01:02:00.540 --> 01:02:04.554
The CO2 greenhouse gas policy
discussion is stalled forever

01:02:04.554 --> 01:02:05.970
and it will take
many, many years.

01:02:05.970 --> 01:02:07.970
That's not a reason not
to do anything about it,

01:02:07.970 --> 01:02:09.440
but you have to
be very much aware

01:02:09.440 --> 01:02:13.340
that really effective
policymaking is not

01:02:13.340 --> 01:02:16.680
in the foreseeable future unless
there's some big disaster.

01:02:16.680 --> 01:02:19.130
If something terrible
happens and lots of people

01:02:19.130 --> 01:02:22.720
die for something that can be
connected with climate change,

01:02:22.720 --> 01:02:23.220
trust me.

01:02:23.220 --> 01:02:25.210
Next day, you have regulation.

01:02:25.210 --> 01:02:26.920
But right now, the
way things are moving,

01:02:26.920 --> 01:02:28.900
you saw the mercury processes.

01:02:28.900 --> 01:02:30.176
How many [INAUDIBLE] in total?

01:02:30.176 --> 01:02:30.676
12?

01:02:30.676 --> 01:02:31.700
14?

01:02:31.700 --> 01:02:35.350
From the science consensus
to getting all the things--

01:02:35.350 --> 01:02:38.730
and you saw that all this
is just really compromises.

01:02:38.730 --> 01:02:41.333
It's never going to give you
to taking specific action.

01:02:41.333 --> 01:02:43.690
So you have to be
very aware of that.

01:02:43.690 --> 01:02:47.050
And you saw the view of
the NGOs which, of course,

01:02:47.050 --> 01:02:50.380
they are really committed
usually to the moral argument.

01:02:50.380 --> 01:02:52.419
That's their main driving force.

01:02:52.419 --> 01:02:53.960
They believe this
is the right thing.

01:02:53.960 --> 01:02:56.950
They are the
conscience of humanity

01:02:56.950 --> 01:03:00.630
and they want to move companies
to do the moral thing.

01:03:00.630 --> 01:03:02.690
And companies need
to push all the time.

01:03:02.690 --> 01:03:05.160
I want to do the moral
thing, but that's not

01:03:05.160 --> 01:03:06.970
where my strengths are.

01:03:06.970 --> 01:03:09.200
The best way is to try to
do something in between.

01:03:09.200 --> 01:03:10.880
OK, good, so we've
[INAUDIBLE] us

01:03:10.880 --> 01:03:14.240
to how to make this
happen in a company.

01:03:14.240 --> 01:03:18.060
So this is the talk I give
to executives when they ask

01:03:18.060 --> 01:03:19.760
me, oh, so give me a process.

01:03:19.760 --> 01:03:22.439
People like, like, five step
process or three checklist

01:03:22.439 --> 01:03:22.980
or something.

01:03:22.980 --> 01:03:24.980
But ultimately, it's
something like this, right?

01:03:24.980 --> 01:03:26.650
It's what we were
talking earlier.

01:03:26.650 --> 01:03:31.520
It's that you have to understand
the pressures of your business

01:03:31.520 --> 01:03:33.540
which we have talked
to ad nauseam.

01:03:33.540 --> 01:03:36.420
And you have to make
this decision that

01:03:36.420 --> 01:03:41.280
is, say no to some
things and don't go them.

01:03:41.280 --> 01:03:43.205
Somehow, do not do them.

01:03:43.205 --> 01:03:47.500
And not do them means do the
minimum, do the right thing,

01:03:47.500 --> 01:03:49.860
or do the things [? where ?]
to mitigate your risk

01:03:49.860 --> 01:03:52.200
and pick a few that you
really want to do well.

01:03:52.200 --> 01:03:54.470
And that's a kind of--
and to do that property,

01:03:54.470 --> 01:03:57.280
you have to measure somehow.

01:03:57.280 --> 01:03:59.560
And once you do
that measurement,

01:03:59.560 --> 01:04:03.100
then you really set
goals and targets,

01:04:03.100 --> 01:04:08.540
which these set goals and
targets is the one thing that I

01:04:08.540 --> 01:04:11.190
unfortunately cannot teach you.

01:04:11.190 --> 01:04:13.850
Because I don't
know how to do it.

01:04:13.850 --> 01:04:16.660
I wish I could tell you
what's the best goal to do.

01:04:16.660 --> 01:04:19.370
10% reduction of
waste per years?

01:04:19.370 --> 01:04:20.645
Zero waste by 2020?

01:04:20.645 --> 01:04:22.240
I mean, what is the best goal?

01:04:22.240 --> 01:04:24.170
So Alexis, you have
a better advice

01:04:24.170 --> 01:04:26.151
to our esteemed students?

01:04:26.151 --> 01:04:28.150
STUDENT: Talking it through
companies, you know.

01:04:28.150 --> 01:04:30.087
They assess where
they're at currently,

01:04:30.087 --> 01:04:31.462
what quantities--
if you're going

01:04:31.462 --> 01:04:36.120
to look at waste management,
they look at how they-- a lot

01:04:36.120 --> 01:04:38.820
of companies will do a pilot
and see how they can do it

01:04:38.820 --> 01:04:41.430
within the first year and look
at what the competitors are

01:04:41.430 --> 01:04:44.350
proposing and other
people in the industry

01:04:44.350 --> 01:04:45.940
and if they're the
first of the type.

01:04:45.940 --> 01:04:47.940
The one thing that I've
read in a lot of reports

01:04:47.940 --> 01:04:51.050
is that, you know, we're
putting high goals out here.

01:04:51.050 --> 01:04:53.369
We may not hit them,
so better go high.

01:04:53.369 --> 01:04:55.160
Then it's almost worse
if you put low goals

01:04:55.160 --> 01:04:56.810
because then you'll get
critiqued for not shooting

01:04:56.810 --> 01:04:57.160
high enough.

01:04:57.160 --> 01:04:58.710
So you're never
really going to win,

01:04:58.710 --> 01:05:01.572
but they go through
a large assessment

01:05:01.572 --> 01:05:03.780
of what they think they can
do internally and looking

01:05:03.780 --> 01:05:05.940
at competitors and kind
of gauging it that way.

01:05:05.940 --> 01:05:11.017
STUDENT: What are thoughts about
levels of today or levels of--

01:05:11.017 --> 01:05:11.850
PROFESSOR: Go ahead.

01:05:11.850 --> 01:05:14.200
Yeah, have some thoughts, but
you have some thoughts as well?

01:05:14.200 --> 01:05:15.960
STUDENT: I'm just wondering
if that's a good way to start.

01:05:15.960 --> 01:05:17.240
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so that's
a good way to start.

01:05:17.240 --> 01:05:18.710
So let me just position this.

01:05:18.710 --> 01:05:22.590
If you look at any company, they
have these vision goals, right?

01:05:22.590 --> 01:05:25.815
Which just put
clear to the company

01:05:25.815 --> 01:05:27.190
where are your
priorities, right?

01:05:27.190 --> 01:05:30.710
We're going to have a zero
emissions car by 2050, right?

01:05:30.710 --> 01:05:34.020
Maybe 2049, maybe 2030,
whatever the number is.

01:05:34.020 --> 01:05:40.380
So you definitely need to have
this idea of that vision target

01:05:40.380 --> 01:05:42.380
that tends to be
super aggressive.

01:05:42.380 --> 01:05:42.980
Why?

01:05:42.980 --> 01:05:45.104
Because that just tells
you where your priority is.

01:05:45.104 --> 01:05:46.900
That's a way to say,
this matters to me.

01:05:46.900 --> 01:05:48.562
This is why I want to do it.

01:05:48.562 --> 01:05:50.520
And that's what you see
in all the CSR reports.

01:05:50.520 --> 01:05:51.850
That's the number one.

01:05:51.850 --> 01:05:55.500
The next one they do
is like Alexis said.

01:05:55.500 --> 01:05:58.370
And this goes back
to the process

01:05:58.370 --> 01:06:02.850
of setting goals and
targets in any organization.

01:06:02.850 --> 01:06:06.280
Who here has experience
in a company doing

01:06:06.280 --> 01:06:09.445
financial targets for sales?

01:06:09.445 --> 01:06:10.422
Who has done it?

01:06:10.422 --> 01:06:12.130
Who has been part of
a process for sales?

01:06:12.130 --> 01:06:13.660
How is that done?

01:06:13.660 --> 01:06:15.590
How does it happen when
you, like a company--

01:06:15.590 --> 01:06:17.750
I'm the CEO of a
company and I need

01:06:17.750 --> 01:06:20.480
to go next quarter or
next year for my guidance

01:06:20.480 --> 01:06:21.730
for Wall Street.

01:06:21.730 --> 01:06:23.590
And I need to set up
goals and targets.

01:06:23.590 --> 01:06:24.450
How do I do that?

01:06:24.450 --> 01:06:26.880
STUDENT: Well, we would just
have like an annual operating

01:06:26.880 --> 01:06:29.680
plan process where basically
they would bring it

01:06:29.680 --> 01:06:32.135
all the representatives
from all the sales divisions

01:06:32.135 --> 01:06:33.700
and they would come
in and say here's

01:06:33.700 --> 01:06:36.284
our major-- they could come in
one by one, like, all the adds,

01:06:36.284 --> 01:06:38.408
and say, here are the
customers that fall under us.

01:06:38.408 --> 01:06:39.840
Here's what we
think. [INAUDIBLE]

01:06:39.840 --> 01:06:41.548
we forecast the business
that we're going

01:06:41.548 --> 01:06:43.085
to do based on XYZ reasons.

01:06:43.085 --> 01:06:44.460
So therefore,
[INAUDIBLE] number.

01:06:44.460 --> 01:06:46.340
And they would roll
all that up into one.

01:06:46.340 --> 01:06:48.865
And operation [INAUDIBLE]

01:06:48.865 --> 01:06:50.740
PROFESSOR: So they get
a meeting and everyone

01:06:50.740 --> 01:06:51.573
comes with a number.

01:06:51.573 --> 01:06:54.560
And that guys went back to his
team beforehand and said, guys,

01:06:54.560 --> 01:06:56.200
I have a meeting
tomorrow with the CEO.

01:06:56.200 --> 01:06:57.840
How much are we going to sell?

01:06:57.840 --> 01:06:59.740
And the guy asked the other
guy how much I'm going to sell.

01:06:59.740 --> 01:07:01.490
Eventually, someone that
really knows what happens

01:07:01.490 --> 01:07:03.160
says, oh yeah,
have 20 customers.

01:07:03.160 --> 01:07:05.080
I predict my 20% growth.

01:07:05.080 --> 01:07:06.630
I see these opportunities.

01:07:06.630 --> 01:07:08.330
And they roll it
up and then they

01:07:08.330 --> 01:07:09.886
could make some guesses, right?

01:07:09.886 --> 01:07:12.260
And they just-- I rounded up
the number [INAUDIBLE] good.

